Here's the recommended approach:

## 1. Define Resource Dictionaries per theme

Create separate XAML resource dictionaries:

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Repeat for `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with matching keys.

## 2. Swap dictionaries at runtime

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public void ApplyTheme(string theme)
    {
        var mergedDictionaries = Current.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove existing theme dictionary (always last in collection)
        if (mergedDictionaries.LastOrDefault() is { } existing)
            mergedDictionaries.Remove(existing);

        var dict = theme switch
        {
            "Dark" => new Resources.Styles.DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new Resources.Styles.HighContrastTheme(),
            _ => new Resources.Styles.LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDictionaries.Add(dict);
    }
}
```

## 3. Reference colors via `DynamicResource`

Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so values update live:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" Text="Hello" />
</ContentPage>
```

## 4. Settings page wiring

```csharp
// In your SettingsViewModel or code-behind
void OnThemeSelected(string chosen)
{
    Preferences.Set("AppTheme", chosen);          // persist choice
    ((App)Application.Current).ApplyTheme(chosen); // apply immediately
}
```

Load the saved preference on startup in `App`'s constructor:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ApplyTheme(Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light"));
}
```

## Key points

| Concern | Solution |
|---------|----------|
| Instant switch | `DynamicResource` + replacing the merged dictionary |
| Persistence | `Preferences` API (or any settings store) |
| Consistency | Use identical keys across all three dictionaries |
| Styles/templates | Define `Style` objects in each theme dict that reference the color keys |

This pattern keeps themes fully decoupled and lets you add new ones by simply creating another `ResourceDictionary`.
